Population Health Impact and Economic Consequences of Storms

Ben Kesseler

May 22, 2016

Synopsis

This report examines the U.S. National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration’s (NOAA) storm database, comparing economic damages, injuries, and fatalities. All analysis was performed at the national level, ignoring specific locations. Individual “events” are not easily determined to assess impacts per “event”, so impacts are considered in aggregate over time.

The most damaging and dangerous event types are tornados, hurricanes/typhoons, thunderstorm winds, lightning, hail, floods, storm surges/tides, rip currents, and heat.

Heat (combining heat and excessive heat) is the most dangerous event in terms of fatalities, and second most dangerous in terms of injuries, while causing little economic damage, so it should be prepared for in warm climates.

Tornados are very damaging in both health and economic terms, and should be prepared for in areas prone to experience them.

Floods are extremely damaging economically, while also impacting health fairly severely, so flood prone regions should take relevant precautions.

Hurricanes and typhoons, perhaps because of the advanced warning usually available, cause less impact to health, while causing the second highest economic damages.

Data Processing

Loading the Raw Data

Library packages are loaded for the entire analysis. Code output has been suppressed for this code only.

We start with the NOAA Storm Data that is archived on the course website and documented here and here.

source_url <- "https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/repdata%2Fdata%2FStormData.csv.bz2"
target_local_archive <- "storm_data.csv.bz2"

if (!file.exists(target_local_archive)) {
  download.file(source_url,target_local_archive)
}

storm_data <- read_csv(target_local_archive, na = "NA")

Initial Cleaning

Each row is a very detailed description of a location, event type, and damage, if any. Actual logical events such as a regional storm or other weather impact might entail many rows, and there is no obvious way to usefully aggregate the rows to logical events.

The analysis covers the entire United States, so location is not important.

As a result, the data will be aggregated by event type at the year level. This will allow the analysis to calculate the impact at an annual level if needed, and across the entire time period for the main analysis.

Once the data is loaded from the .csv.bz2 file, I keep only the year, event type, fatalities, injuries, property damage, and crop damage.

I convert the economic impacts into a consistent scale. I’m unsure of the meaning of non-standard exponents in the data, so I’m treating them as 1, after documenting their prevalence.

storm_data_cleaned <- storm_data[, c("BGN_DATE",
                                     "EVTYPE",
                                     "FATALITIES",
                                     "INJURIES",
                                     "PROPDMG",
                                     "PROPDMGEXP",
                                     "CROPDMG",
                                     "CROPDMGEXP"
                                     )
                                 ]

colnames(storm_data_cleaned) <- c("BGN_DATE",
                                  "event_type",
                                  "fatalities",
                                  "injuries",
                                  "property_damage",
                                  "property_damage_exponent",
                                  "crop_damage",
                                  "crop_damage_exponent"
                                  )

storm_data_cleaned$year <- year(as.POSIXct(storm_data_cleaned$BGN_DATE,
                                           format = "%m/%d/%Y"))

mappable_exponents_property <- sum(storm_data_cleaned$property_damage_exponent == "B") +
                               sum(storm_data_cleaned$property_damage_exponent == "M") +
                               sum(storm_data_cleaned$property_damage_exponent == "K") +
                               sum(storm_data_cleaned$property_damage_exponent == "")

mappable_exponents_crop <- sum(storm_data_cleaned$crop_damage_exponent == "B") +
                           sum(storm_data_cleaned$crop_damage_exponent == "M") +
                           sum(storm_data_cleaned$crop_damage_exponent == "K") +
                           sum(storm_data_cleaned$crop_damage_exponent == "")

percent_unmappable_property <- 1 - mappable_exponents_property / nrow(storm_data_cleaned)

percent_unmappable_crop <- 1 - mappable_exponents_crop / nrow(storm_data_cleaned)

So 0.0364% of property damage records have unmappable exponents, and 0.00543% of crop damage records have unmappable exponents. That’s a very small percent of the records, so treating them as 1 should be reasonable.

I now convert things to a consistent numeric scale, so summation functions will work properly.

scalar_mapping <- data.frame("property_damage_exponent" = c("B","M","K"),
                             "property_damage_numeric_exponent" = c(1000000000,
                                                                    1000000,
                                                                    1000),
                             "crop_damage_exponent" = c("B","M","K"),
                             "crop_damage_numeric_exponent" = c(1000000000,
                                                                1000000,
                                                                1000)
                            )

storm_data_cleaned <- merge(storm_data_cleaned,
                            scalar_mapping[, 
                                           c("property_damage_exponent",
                                             "property_damage_numeric_exponent"
                                            )
                                          ],
                            all.x = TRUE)
storm_data_cleaned$property_damage_numeric_exponent[
  is.na(storm_data_cleaned$property_damage_numeric_exponent)
  ] <- 1

storm_data_cleaned <- merge(storm_data_cleaned,
                            scalar_mapping[, 
                                           c("crop_damage_exponent",
                                             "crop_damage_numeric_exponent"
                                            )
                                          ],
                            all.x = TRUE)
storm_data_cleaned$crop_damage_numeric_exponent[
  is.na(storm_data_cleaned$crop_damage_numeric_exponent)
  ] <- 1

storm_data_cleaned$property_damage <- storm_data_cleaned$property_damage * 
                                      storm_data_cleaned$property_damage_numeric_exponent

storm_data_cleaned$crop_damage <- storm_data_cleaned$crop_damage * 
                                  storm_data_cleaned$crop_damage_numeric_exponent

storm_data_cleaned$economic_damage <- storm_data_cleaned$property_damage + 
                                      storm_data_cleaned$crop_damage

Data Aggregation

Now I will summarize the data at the level needed for plotting and further exploration - annual by event type.

storm_data_cleaned <- storm_data_cleaned[, c("year",
                                             "event_type",
                                             "fatalities",
                                             "injuries",
                                             "economic_damage")]

storm_data_summary <- aggregate(. ~ year + event_type,
                                data = storm_data_cleaned,
                                FUN = sum)

storm_data_count <- aggregate(fatalities ~ year + event_type,
                              data = storm_data_cleaned,
                              FUN = length)

storm_data_summary <- cbind(storm_data_summary,storm_data_count$fatalities)

storm_data_summary$count <- storm_data_count$fatalities

count_by_year <- aggregate(count ~ year, data = storm_data_summary, FUN = sum)

count_by_year_table <- data.frame("year1" = count_by_year[1:16, 1],

Event Type Clean-up

                                data = storm_data_summary[, c("event_type",

                                                          ],

After minimal text formatting, I find that when comparing to the expected 48 event types, I’m unable to match 23.6% of the non-zero events, which account for 19.1% of the economic damage, 12.5% of the injuries, and 14.4% of the fatalities.

This clearly needs some work.

storm_data_final <- storm_data_summary[storm_data_summary$event_match == 1, ]
storm_data_final$event_type <- factor(storm_data_final$event_type)

storm_data_final$combined_health <- storm_data_final$injuries + 
                                    storm_data_final$fatalities

storm_data_final$event_type <- factor(storm_data_final$event_type,
                                      levels = storm_data_final$event_type[
                                        order(storm_data_final$combined_health,
                                              decreasing = TRUE)])

storm_data_final_plot1 <- head(storm_data_final[
  order(-storm_data_final$combined_health), ], 20)

storm_data_final_plot1 <- melt(data = storm_data_final_plot1[, c("event_type",
                                                                 "fatalities",
                                                                 "injuries")
                                                            ], id="event_type")

storm_data_final_plot1$variable <- as.factor(toTitleCase(
    as.character(storm_data_final_plot1$variable)))

First_Plot <- ggplot(data = storm_data_final_plot1,
                       aes(x = event_type, y = value, fill = variable)) +
                geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
                theme_bw() +
                coord_flip() +
                ggtitle("Injuries & Fatalities by Event Type") +
                xlab("Event Types") +
                ylab("Injuries & Fatalities") + 
                scale_fill_manual(values = c(Fatalities = "red", Injuries = "orange")) +
                theme(legend.position = c(0.9, 0.8), 
                      legend.title = element_blank(),
                      panel.grid.major.y = element_line(colour = "#808080"))

storm_data_final_plot2 <- head(storm_data_final[
  order(-storm_data_final$combined_health), ], 20)

Second_Plot <- ggplot(data = storm_data_final_plot2, aes(x = injuries, 
                                                         y = fatalities)) + 
  geom_point() +
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("Injuries vs Fatalities by Event Type") +
  xlab("Injuries") +
  ylab("Fatalities") +
  geom_label_repel(data = subset(storm_data_final_plot2, 
                                 (injuries > 1500 | fatalities > 250)),
                   aes(label = event_type))

storm_data_final_plot3 <- storm_data_final_plot2
storm_data_final_plot3$ratio <- storm_data_final_plot2$fatalities / storm_data_final_plot2$injuries

Third_Plot <- ggplot(data = storm_data_final_plot3, aes(x = event_type, y = ratio, fill = ratio)) + 
  theme_bw() + 
  ggtitle("Fatality to Injury Ratio by Event Type") +
  xlab("Event Types") +
  ylab("Ratio of Fatalities to Injuries") + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") + 
  coord_flip() +
  scale_fill_gradient("ratio", low = "orange", high = "red") +
  theme(legend.position = c(0.85, 0.15),
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.direction = "horizontal")

Results

Fatality, Injury, and Economic Damage Sources

I need to examine the distribution of injuries, fatalaties, and economic damage by the event types present in this data.

I’ll be using top 20 for most of these analyses, to make the plots easier to review.

Note, all of the preparation for these plots occurred above, in the data processing section, but the plots are presented and discussed here.

Figure 1 - Injuries & Fatality Exploration

grid.arrange(First_Plot, Second_Plot, Third_Plot, ncol = 1)

The first plot shows injuries and fatalities for the top 20 event types. The second plot shows injuries vs fatalities for the same subset of events. The third plot shows the ratio of fatalities to injuries, to demonstrate which events are the most dangerous, independent of overall prevalence.

Fatalities and injuries seem to be correlated, although Tornados cause signifigantly more injuries than any other event. However, Rip Currents are more dangerous to life, independent of overall risk of encountering the events.

Figure 2 - Economic Damage Exploration

Fourth_Plot

Economic Damage in Billions of USD is displayed, for the top 20 event types. Flood may be somewhat overstated as all flood events must have a damage statement, even if an estimate.

Floods, hurricanes/typhoons, storm surges/tides, and tornados are the most damaging events, economically.

Figure 3 - Economic Damage vs Injuries & Fatalities by Event Type

grid.arrange(Fifth_Plot, Sixth_Plot, ncol = 2)

The first plot shows economic damages vs injuries for all event types. The second plot compares economics damages to fatalities.

Further Exploration

This analysis did not cover events over time or by location, while data on both was available in the raw data. A further analysis could plot injuries, fatalities, and economic damage as a density plot over the United States, by utilizing the latitude and longitude present in the data. Similarly, after subsetting to post-1994 data to ensure consistent reporting methods, events and damages could be compared over time, to determine if any events are occuring more frequently, or are causing more impact, over time.
